03902nam a22005175i 9780226025902DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802260259027 a10.7208/97802260259022doi  a(DE-B1597)524523  a(OCoLC)844939934  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aART0000002bisacsh1 aGiuliani, Luca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImage and Myth :bA History of Pictorial Narration in Greek Art /cLuca Giuliani. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b87 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: The Pictorial Deluge and the Study of Visual Culture -- t1. Images and Texts Compared: A Diagnosis of Contrasts -- t2. Images of the World: The Eighth Century -- t3. The Advent of Pictorial Narratives in the Seventh Century -- t4. Playing with Writing in the Eighth, Seventh, and Sixth Centuries -- t5. Directing the Gaze in the Sixth and Fifth Centuries -- t6. Images in the Pull of Text: From the Fifth to the Fourth Century -- t7. Pictures for Readers: The Birth of the Illustration in the Second Century -- t8. Looking Back: Pitfalls and Nodes -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tName & Subject Index -- tIndex of Ancient Greek Artworks0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn museum visits, we pass by beautiful, well-preserved vases from ancient Greece—but how often do we understand what the images on them depict? In Image and Myth, Luca Giuliani tells the stories behind the pictures, exploring how artists of antiquity had to determine which motifs or historical and mythic events to use to tell an underlying story while also keeping in mind the tastes and expectations of paying clients. Covering the range of Greek style and its growth between the early Archaic and Hellenistic periods, Giuliani describes the intellectual, social, and artistic contexts in which the images were created. He reveals that developments in Greek vase painting were driven as much by the times as they were by tradition—the better-known the story, the less leeway the artists had in interpreting it. As literary culture transformed from an oral tradition, in which stories were always in flux, to the stability of written texts, the images produced by artists eventually became nothing more than illustrations of canonical works. At once a work of cultural and art history, Image and Myth builds a new way of understanding the visual culture of ancient Greece.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt, GreekxThemes, motives. 0aMythology, Greek, in art. 0aNarrative artzGreece. 0aVase-painting, Greek. 7aART / General.2bisacsh1 aO'Donnell, Joseph.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226025902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226025902.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles